compute.effect.size <- function(df.coef){

df.es <- df.coef[,1:3]
n <- length(df.es$Parameter)
m <- df.es$Parameter


for(i in 1:n){
  if(grepl("log",m[i])==T){
    df.es[i,2] <- 1.01^(df.coef[i,2])
    df.es[i,3] <- 1.01^(df.coef[i,2])*log(1.01)*df.coef[i,3]
  }else if(m[i] %in% c("NDVI","Bog","Arable","Forest","Temp")){
    df.es[i,2] <- exp(df.coef[i,2]*0.01)
    df.es[i,3] <- 0.01*df.coef[i,2]*df.coef[i,3]
  }else if(m[i] %in% c("TNdep","TSdep")){
    df.es[i,2] <- exp(df.coef[i,2]*25)
    df.es[i,3] <- 25*exp(df.coef[i,2]*25)*df.coef[i,3]
  } else {
    df.es[i,2] <- exp(df.coef) # effect size for temperature???
  }
}

df.es$Percent <- 100*(df.es$Estimate-1)

return(df.es)

}

1 Introduction

Forest management is an essential tool in achieving the commitments in the Fennoscandian climate policies (Sundnes et al. 2020). In line with the Declaration on Forest and Land Use signed on November 2021(UN Climate Change Conference UK 2021), the Fennoscandian governments consider forest as a leverage for offsetting their carbon emissions and reaching their zero-emission goals (Nordic Council of Ministers 2021) Norway, Sweden and Finland (collectively labelled Fennoscandia) are not subject to deforestation with 43.5, 65.5 and 70.9% (OECD 2020), respectively, of their territories covered with forest.These boreal forests hold large belowground and peatland pools of organic carbon. During the last century, the Fennoscandian forest volume has increased some 25% (ref). Most of this is a result from massive forest planting campaigns in the 50ies and 60ies, but forest growth has also benefited from a milder climate, with longer growing seasons, as well as the accumulation of reactive nitrogen from long-range transported air pollution and potentially also increased atmospheric concentrations of CO2. This increased forest volume also implies a strong C-sequestration, and current policies in the Nordics promote the intensification of the forest industry. In Norway, the ministry of Environment (Miljdirektoratet) subsidies densification of the planted areas and the afforestation of new so-called Climate forests (Miljdirektoratet 2013). In Fennoscandia as a whole, timber industry is a major economical resource (Royal Swedish Academy of Agriculture and Forestry 2015). Forestry products account for 23% of the Swedish total exports and the standing biomass doubled over the last 100 years (Nringsdepartementet 2018). Formas, the Swedish government research council for sustainable development, promotes bioeconomy as a major climate mitigation tool (Formas 2012). Similarly, in Finland the national subsidy schemes aim at intensifying the forestry sector. A fifth of the Finnish export of goods come from the wood industry. (Ministry of Agriculture and Forestry 2014). The Finnish forest legislation was renewed in the 2010s to improve its competitiveness while conserving its goals in terms of sustainability.

The planned intensification of forest management and afforestation has, on the other hand, raised concern regarding the water quality (Norsk Vann 2019). In Norway, 90% of the raw water used for drinking water comes from surface waters (Energifakta Norge n.d.). Browning has potential impact on the required raw water treatment to ensure potability of water (Eikebrokk, Vogt, and Liltved 2004). In addition, browning impact lakes by reducing light absorbance, and thus reducing primary production (Karlsson 2007), while at the same time increasing the CO2 and CH4 emissions from the lakes, especially in small lakes [Yang et al. (2015); Parra et al.ms ; Wit et al. (2018)], further increasing the net heterotrophy that prevails in boreal lakes (Tranvik et al. 2009). Reduced primary production propagate up the trophic ladder and also affect fish, both via reduced productivity, but also by affecting visual feeding in fish (Finstad et al. 2014) and thermal regimes (Karlsson et al. 2009; Craig et al. 2017). The current browning of freshwater lakes and rivers also entails the darkening of coastal waters, delaying phytoplankton spring blooms and decreasing coastal primary production (Opdal, Lindemann, and Aksnes 2019). Understanding the governing factors for TOC concentration under local anthropogenic and regional climatic stresses is therefore essential to forecast its potential detrimental effects to the water quality and ecosystem services.

NDVI and Forest cover are both proxy for the biomass amount on the catchment. However, they are poorly correlated (0.62) and are not expected to have exactly the same effect on TOC concentration in time. To investigate the effect of an increase of forest cover in Norway, Sweden and Finland, in line with the forest policies in these three countries, an alternative model was fitted using Forest (instead of NDVI), Bog and Runoff as predictors based on the Northern Lake Survey (1995). Then, the model was tested with the 2019 survey and the forecast made for 2100, when planted trees will have reached maturity.

2 Spatial error model with Forest as predictor

A Spatial error model was fitted on the Fennoscandia dataset with Forest, logRunoff and Bog as predictors.

Figure 1: Effect size for SELM model with forest as predictor instead of NDVI

To compare their relative impact, a second SELM was fitted with Forest replacing NDVI as explanatory variable. It renders a relatively small effect size by a 1% increase in Forest (Figure 1) compared to a 1% increase in NDVI (Figure 2).

Replacing NDVI with Forest enhance the relative impact of Bogs. I.e., 15% (Figure 1) compared to 1% (Figure 2) for Fennoscandian dataset, and even more for the model based on the Norwegian dataset. The effect size of a 1% increase in runoff remains unchanged at -0.41% and -0.4%, based on the Fennoscandian dataset and Norwegian dataset, respectively.

3 Fitting NIVA data with forest

Fitting the log(TOC) concentration using Forest as predictor instead of NDVI results in a reasonable fit, as displayed on Figure 3, even if the lower values are over-estimated and the higher values are over-estimated. This is a similar pattern compared to the model fitted with NDVI, where the high TOC concentrations in the south-east of Norway were under-estimated. The maps of the predicted and observed TOC concentrations are shown on Figure 4.

4 Forecast of mean TOC concentration with an increase of forest cover

An increase in forest cover as a nature-based solution (NbS) to sequester CO2 to abate climate change Lehtonen and Mkip (2021), Region Skne (2020), Haugland et al. (2014) may have an impact on the TOC concentration in lakes. In this section, we use the model fitted in section 3.5 to predict the TOC concentration in water regions pending an increase in forest cover.

4.1 TOC prediction for 1995 on water regions

The water regions model is based on water districts determined by an elevation model. Hence, the mean TOC concentration in the water bodies for each of these water regions was not sampled. Therefore, the original TOC concentration in 1995 was modeled thanks to the SELM model fitted with Forest, NDVI and logRunoff as predictor on the Northern Lake Survey Data. The catchment characteristics (NDVI, Forest and logRunoff) were extracted in the same way as in the model with NDVI as predictor. The resulting mean TOC concentration is shown on . As proved by the test on observed TOC concentration for the 2019-dataset, high TOC concentrations are likely to be underestimated in the south-east of Norway and in other regions with high TOC concentration, like south Sweden.

sem.forest.fen <- readRDS("sem.forest.fen.Rdata")
wr.sf.95 <- readRDS("WR/wr.sf.95.rds")
fm <- logTOC~Forest+logRunoff+Bog
wr.pred <- predict(sem.forest.fen,wr.sf.95,wr.kmat, pred.type = "TS",legacy.mixed = F, zero.policy = T) %>% as.data.frame()

sem.pred.forest.wr <- cbind(wr.sf.95,wr.pred$fit)
sem.pred.forest.wr$TOC95 <- exp(sem.pred.forest.wr$wr.pred.fit)

saveRDS(sem.pred.forest.wr,"WR/sem.pred.forest.wr.rds")

map.fit.forest <- ggplot()+geom_sf(data = st_as_sf(sem.pred.forest.wr), aes(fill = TOC95, col = TOC95))+

4.2 Prediction of forest increase in Norway, Sweden and Finland

We assessed the increase in forest cover based on numbers presented in policy papers. In Finland, 26,18 million ha LUKE (n.d.) are covered with forest and 90 000 are expected to be planted by 2065 Lehtonen and Mkip (2021). This represents roughly an mean increase of 0,34%. In Sweden, the forest covers 28 million hectares Swedish Forest Agency (2012). The Swedish forest policy includes the afforestation of 190 000 ha Statens Offentliga Utredningar (2020), representing a 0,68% increase. In Norway, the forest covers 8,443 million ha and the plan for afforestation is to increase this cover up to 9,78 million hectare, i.e.16%.

However, the potential increase in the proportion of forest cover differs between the water regions as the proportion of forest in a region with a 100% forest cover cannot increase further. Likewise, it is unlikely that a water region with a 0% forest cover (bare rocks, glaciers) can be afforested. Therefore, the potential increase of forest cover was calculated using a beta-distribution shape (see Supplementary 3). The increase was calculated to be, on average, 0,34% for Finland, 0.68% for Sweden and 16% for Norway.

5 Conclusion

In this study, we compare the difference between two modeled values (TOC concentration fitted for 1995 and TOC concentration fitted for 2100). Therefore, we assume that the underestimation effect, for regions with high TOC concentration, is cancelled by the double-fit and that the difference in TOC concentration is a valid indicator for future changes. Moreover, the regions with high TOC concentration are also the regions with currently high forest cover. In these regions, the increase of forest cover is expected to be low, therefore the change of TOC concentration is also likely to be low.

In addition, an increase in forest cover will not immediately lead to an increase in TOC concentration, as soil formation and runoff processes are long-term processes that might not be captured in a space-for-time analysis. However, by comparing the predictions for 2100, i.e., after the full growth of the new forests), we assume that the new forest soils will have a pool of SOC comparable to the old forest soils. actually how much time does it take to form new forest soil similar to old forest???

As the previsions for planting new forest are much higher in Norway then in Sweden, the difference in TOC in the future is also highest in Norway. The forest increase is between 0 and 2% in Sweden and Finland, depending on the catchment, and the increase in TOC concentration remains under 0.5 mg/L in most of them. In Norway, the maximum increase is around 1.5 mg/L, in the North and in mid-Norge.
